  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="30" relname="preparation">Harry Marks has said it well. </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="concession"> I have been veryglad indeed to
learn from all the mail about Respect,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="21" relname="span"> but much of it has not
addressed my continuing concern. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="30" relname="span"> What is the ultimate purpose
of doing STS and related things? </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="unless"> Unless we have some notion
about this,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="31" relname="span"> we can hardly tell whether we are doing our work
well,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> nor can we tell whether there are ways to do it better. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
I am sorry now about the title I put on my first message about
this,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="33" relname="span"> because it seems to have diverted attention to whether
and how we should seek the approval and cooperation of working
scientists. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="22" relname="span"> (In passing, I did not mean to suggest that
&quot;respect&quot; would have to be built on friendly collaboration and
mutual support;</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> the hardest taskmaster might elicit respect
without approval or friendly feelings.)</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="concession">

I don&apos;t want to get us into an infinite regress,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="27" relname="span"> but a step or
two in that direction might help.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="25" relname="list">  What are we really trying
to accomplish in the long run?</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="25" relname="list">  What lies behink our concern
with individual disciplines, or programs, or research
projects, or scientists, or whatever? </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="25" relname="list"> Do we want to make a
difference in anything that matters? </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="25" relname="list"> If so, what and how? </segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="24" relname="span">
Steve Fuller has written a bit on this, which I found quite
informative,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="23" relname="elaboration"> and so have Bernie Lieberman and one or two
others,</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="26" relname="span"> but I don&apos;t feel much closer to a well formulated and 
broadly accepted answer.</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="19" relname="elaboration">  Am I asking for too much?</segment>
